#week-title("Two", "Setting the Stage: Formal Practice & Duration")

=== Core Teaching

A proper vigil is a formal practice. It is not something to be rushed between
other tasks. The practitioner does not seek visions or dramatic experiences;
they seek to *witness*.

Duration is key. A proper vigil should ideally last a minimum of two hours.
This length allows the surface noise of the mind to settle and the deeper,
receptive layers of perception to awaken. Beginning students may work toward
this duration, starting with shorter sessions if necessary, but the two-hour
mark is the threshold for a "deep" vigil.

=== Topics This Week

- Preparation for the vigil: what to bring (journal, nothing else)
- The importance of duration and silence
- Overcoming the mind's resistance to "doing nothing"

#inner-work[
  *The First Formal Vigil*

  Conduct your first formal vigil this month with your original plant (the one
  you chose in Month 1).

  *The Practice:*
  Find a comfortable position where you can observe the plant without strain.
  Sit for at least one hour (aiming for two). Bring nothing but your journal and
  pen. Do not read or use your phone. Observe. Notice the quality of light through
  leaves, the movement of insects, the way the plant responds to wind.

  Record your notes *immediately after* the session, not during it.
]

